text.tspan: show, don't tell
Going by the concept of show, don't tell, I went with a multi-level donut chart to compare the
breakdown of the transcript lines across both episodes. The multi-level donut chart allows for a quick
visual comparison of dialogue vs no dialogue lines.
It was ultimately the choice between this and stacked bars, where both compare both episodes. Since
my focus is on showing the percentage rather than telling the reader the specific data, I ended up
going with a multi-level donut chart that shows a quick comparison between the percentage of dialogue
vs non-dialogue lines across both episodes. The reason for choosing a multi-level pie chart over multiple
pie charts is because the human eye finds it harder to compare two separate circles, especially when
percentages are close in both charts. While aligning both on top of each other makes it easy to spot the
difference.
parallels / common words
Heavily inspired by a processing sketch that parses words from 9 famous speeches and
displays the results in a custom diagram, I initially wanted to do something very similar
where I am comparing the top used words by character. Going a few weeks over the
deadline, I settled into just comparing the use across both episodes instead, without
the additional complexity of sorting it by character as well.
The stocked bar charts give the user a quick idea of the frequency of a word used
within both episodes, then break it down one level further by visualization how much of
that was during the first vs the latest episode.
sfx word cloud
For my sixth and final chart, I went with the risky choice of a word cloud. While in most majority of
cases, word clouds don't communicate much if at all. Yes, you can't actually read every single word
that was used in the episodes SFX, or actually see how frequent their use is, or any useful data for that
matter. However, numbers and data points aren't that relevant here. The goal of the chart is to give the
viewer a general sense of the most frequent SFX sounds used in both episodes and how they fit with
the series theme, in which case word cloud seemed like the ideal choice.
